# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: urban-metabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:urban-metabolism/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An **agent-based model** (**ABM**) is a computational model for simulating the actions and interactions of an autonomous agent (both individual or collective entities such as organizations or groups) to understand the behavior of a system and what governs its outcomes.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] It combines elements of game theory, complex systems, emergence, computational sociology, multi-agent systems, and evolutionary programming.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Monte Carlo methods are used to understand the stochasticity of these models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Particularly within ecology, an ABM is also called an **individual-based model** (**IBM**).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A review of literature on individual-based models, agent-based models, and multiagent systems shows that ABMs are used in many scientific domains including biology, ecology, and social science.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling is related to, but distinct from, the concept of a **multi-agent system** .
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is a type of microscale model that simulates the simultaneous operations and interactions of multiple agents in an attempt to re-create and predict the appearance of complex phenomena.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The process is one of emergence, which some express as "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In other words, higher-level system properties emerge from the interactions of lower-level subsystems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Or, macro-scale state changes emerge from micro-scale agent behaviors.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Or, simple behaviors (meaning rules followed by agents) generate complex behaviors (meaning state changes at the whole system level).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An individual agent is typically characterized as boundedly rational, presumed to be acting in what it perceives as its their own interests, such as reproduction, economic benefit, or social status, using heuristics or simple decision-making rules.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An ABM agent may experience "learning", adaptation, and reproduction.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is usually composed of (1) numerous agents specified at various scales (typically referred to as agent-granularity), (2) decision-making heuristics, (3) learning rules or adaptive processes,(4) an interaction topology, and (5) an environment.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] An ABM is typically implemented as a computer simulation, either as custom software or using an ABM toolkit.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This software can be then used to test how changes in individual behavior will affect the system's overall behavior.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The idea of agent-based modeling was developed as a relatively simple concept in the late 1940s.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since it requires computation-intensive procedures, it did not become widespread until the 1990s.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The history of the agent-based model can be traced back to the Von Neumann machine, a theoretical machine capable of reproduction.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The device von Neumann proposed would follow precisely detailed instructions to fashion a copy of itself.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The concept was then built upon by von Neumann's friend Stanislaw Ulam, also a mathematician; Ulam suggested that the machine be built on paper, as a collection of cells on a grid.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The idea intrigued von Neumann, who drew it up — creating the first of the devices later termed cellular automata.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Oliver Selfridge's 1958 Pandemonium - A Paradigm for Learning paper was an important early theorectical contribution in establishing agent orientated architecture, though it used the term metaphorical 'demon' instead of agent.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Carl Hewitt 1973 Actor model contained one of the earliest uses of agents as active entities rather than passive structures.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Another advance was introduced by the mathematician John Conway.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] He constructed the well-known Game of Life.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Unlike von Neumann's machine, the Game of Life operated by simple rules in a virtual world in the form of a 2-dimensional checkerboard.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Simula programming language, developed in the mid-1960s and widely implemented by the early 1970s, was the first framework for automating step-by-step agent simulations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] One of the earliest agent-based models in concept was Thomas Schelling's segregation model, which was discussed in his paper "Dynamic Models of Segregation" in 1971.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Though Schelling originally used coins and graph paper rather than computers, his models embodied the basic concept of agent-based models as autonomous agents interacting in a shared environment with an observed aggregate, emergent outcome.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the late 1970s, Paulien Hogeweg and Bruce Hesper began experimenting with individual models of ecology.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] One of their first results was to show that the social structure of bumble-bee colonies emerged as a result of simple rules that govern the behaviour of individual bees.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] They introduced the ToDo principle, referring to the way agents "do what there is to do" at any given time.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the early 1980s, Robert Axelrod hosted a tournament of Prisoner's Dilemma strategies and had them interact in an agent-based manner to determine a winner.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Axelrod would go on to develop many other agent-based models in the field of political science that examine phenomena from ethnocentrism to the dissemination of culture.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] By the late 1980s, Craig Reynolds' work on flocking models contributed to the development of some of the first biological agent-based models that contained social characteristics.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] He tried to model the reality of lively biological agents, known as artificial life, a term coined by Christopher Langton.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] At the same time, during the 1980s, social scientists, mathematicians, operations researchers, and a scattering of people from other disciplines developed Computational and Mathematical Organization Theory (CMOT).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This field grew as a special interest group of The Institute of Management Sciences (TIMS) and its sister society, the Operations Research Society of America (ORSA).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The 1990s were especially notable for the expansion of ABM within the social sciences, one notable effort was the large-scale ABM, Sugarscape, developed by Joshua M.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Epstein and Robert Axtell to simulate and explore the role of social phenomena such as seasonal migrations, pollution, sexual reproduction, combat, and transmission of disease and even culture.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other notable 1990s developments included Carnegie Mellon University's Kathleen Carley ABM, to explore the co-evolution of social networks and culture.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Santa Fe Institute (SFI) was important in encouraging the development of the ABM modeling platform Swarm under the leadership of Christopher Langton.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Research conducted through SFI allowed the expansion of ABM techniques to a number of fields including study of the social and spatial dynamics of small-scale human societies and primates.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] During this 1990s timeframe Nigel Gilbert published the first textbook on Social Simulation: Simulation for the social scientist (1999) and established a journal from the perspective of social sciences: the *Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation* (JASSS).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other than JASSS, agent-based models of any discipline are within scope of SpringerOpen journal *Complex Adaptive Systems Modeling* (CASM).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Through the mid-1990s, the social sciences thread of ABM began to focus on such issues as designing effective teams, understanding the communication required for organizational effectiveness, and the behavior of social networks.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] CMOT—later renamed Computational Analysis of Social and Organizational Systems (CASOS)—incorporated more and more agent-based modeling.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Samuelson (2000) is a good brief overview of the early history, and Samuelson (2005) and Samuelson and Macal (2006) trace the more recent developments.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the late 1990s, the merger of TIMS and ORSA to form INFORMS, and the move by INFORMS from two meetings each year to one, helped to spur the CMOT group to form a separate society, the North American Association for Computational Social and Organizational Sciences (NAACSOS).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Kathleen Carley was a major contributor, especially to models of social networks, obtaining National Science Foundation funding for the annual conference and serving as the first president of NAACSOS.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] She was succeeded by David Sallach of the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory, and then by Michael Prietula of Emory University.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] At about the same time NAACSOS began, the European Social Simulation Association (ESSA) and the Pacific Asian Association for Agent-Based Approach in Social Systems Science (PAAA), counterparts of NAACSOS, were organized.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] As of 2013, these three organizations collaborate internationally.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The First World Congress on Social Simulation was held under their joint sponsorship in Kyoto, Japan, in August 2006.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Second World Congress was held in the northern Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., in July 2008, with George Mason University taking the lead role in local arrangements.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] More recently, Ron Sun developed methods for basing agent-based simulation on models of human cognition, known as cognitive social simulation.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Bill McKelvey, Suzanne Lohmann, Dario Nardi, Dwight Read and others at UCLA have also made significant contributions in organizational behavior and decision-making.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since 1991, UCLA has arranged a conference at Lake Arrowhead, California, that has become another major gathering point for practitioners in this field.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] After the advent of large language models, researchers began applying interacting language models to agent based modeling.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In one widely cited paper, agentic language models interacted in a sandbox environment to perform activities like planning birthday parties and holding elections.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Most computational modeling research describes systems in equilibrium or as moving between equilibria.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling, however, using simple rules, can result in different sorts of complex and interesting behavior.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The three ideas central to agent-based models are agents as objects, emergence, and complexity.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models consist of dynamically interacting rule-based agents.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The systems within which they interact can create real-world-like complexity.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Typically agents are situated in space and time and reside in networks or in lattice-like neighborhoods.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The location of the agents and their responsive behavior are encoded in algorithmic form in computer programs.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In some cases, though not always, the agents may be considered as intelligent and purposeful.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In ecological ABM (often referred to as "individual-based models" in ecology), agents may, for example, be trees in a forest, and would not be considered intelligent, although they may be "purposeful" in the sense of optimizing access to a resource (such as water).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The modeling process is best described as inductive.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The modeler makes those assumptions thought most relevant to the situation at hand and then watches phenomena emerge from the agents' interactions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Sometimes that result is an equilibrium.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Sometimes, however, it is an unintelligible mangle.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In some ways, agent-based models complement traditional analytic methods.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Where analytic methods enable humans to characterize the equilibria of a system, agent-based models allow the possibility of generating those equilibria.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This generative contribution may be the most mainstream of the potential benefits of agent-based modeling.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models can explain the emergence of higher-order patterns—network structures of terrorist organizations and the Internet, power-law distributions in the sizes of traffic jams, wars, and stock-market crashes, and social segregation that persists despite populations of tolerant people.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models also can be used to identify lever points, defined as moments in time in which interventions have extreme consequences, and to distinguish among types of path dependency.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Rather than focusing on stable states, many models consider a system's robustness—the ways that complex systems adapt to internal and external pressures so as to maintain their functionalities.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The task of harnessing that complexity requires consideration of the agents themselves—their diversity, connectedness, and level of interactions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Exploratory Agent-based Modeling Level for developing agent-based models for assessing the feasibility of further research.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This can e.g. be useful for developing proof-of-concept models such as for funding applications without requiring an extensive learning curve for the researchers.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Descriptive Agent-based Modeling (DREAM) for developing descriptions of agent-based models by means of using templates and complex network-based models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Building DREAM models allows model comparison across scientific disciplines.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Validated agent-based modeling using Virtual Overlay Multiagent system (VOMAS) for the development of verified and validated models in a formal manner.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other methods of describing agent-based models include code templates and text-based methods such as the ODD (Overview, Design concepts, and Design Details) protocol.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The role of the environment where agents live, both macro and micro, is also becoming an important factor in agent-based modelling and simulation work.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Simple environment affords simple agents, but complex environments generate diversity of behavior.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] One strength of agent-based modelling is its ability to mediate information flow between scales.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] When additional details about an agent are needed, a researcher can integrate it with models describing the extra details.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] When one is interested in the emergent behaviours demonstrated by the agent population, they can combine the agent-based model with a continuum model describing population dynamics.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the resulting modular model, signal transduction and gene regulation are described by a logical model, metabolism by constraint-based models, cell population dynamics are described by an agent-based model, and systemic cytokine concentrations by ordinary differential equations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In this multi-scale model, the agent-based model occupies the central place and orchestrates every stream of information flow between scales.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been used for developing decision support systems such as for breast cancer.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models are increasingly being used to model pharmacological systems in early stage and pre-clinical research to aid in drug development and gain insights into biological systems that would not be possible *a priori*.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Military applications have also been evaluated.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Moreover, agent-based models have been recently employed to study molecular-level biological systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been written to describe ecological processes at work in ancient systems, such as those in dinosaur environments and more recent ancient systems as well.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models now complement traditional compartmental models, the usual type of epidemiological models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have been shown to be superior to compartmental models in regard to the accuracy of predictions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Recently, ABMs such as CovidSim by epidemiologist Neil Ferguson, have been used to inform public health (nonpharmaceutical) interventions against the spread of SARS-CoV-2.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Epidemiological ABMs have been criticized for simplifying and unrealistic assumptions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Still, they can be useful in informing decisions regarding mitigation and suppression measures in cases when ABMs are accurately calibrated.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The ABMs for such simulations are mostly based on synthetic populations, since the data of the actual population is not always available.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have been used since the mid-1990s to solve a variety of business and technology problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Examples of applications include marketing, organizational behaviour and cognition, team working, supply chain optimization and logistics, modeling of consumer behavior, including word of mouth, social network effects, distributed computing, workforce management, and portfolio management.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] They have also been used to analyze traffic congestion.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Recently, agent based modelling and simulation has been applied to various domains such as studying the impact of publication venues by researchers in the computer science domain (journals versus conferences).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In addition, ABMs have been used to simulate information delivery in ambient assisted environments.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A November 2016 article in arXiv analyzed an agent based simulation of posts spread in Facebook.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the domain of peer-to-peer, ad hoc and other self-organizing and complex networks, the usefulness of agent based modeling and simulation has been shown.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The use of a computer science-based formal specification framework coupled with wireless sensor networks and an agent-based simulation has recently been demonstrated.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent based evolutionary search or algorithm is a new research topic for solving complex optimization problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the realm of team science, agent-based modeling has been utilized to assess the effects of team members' characteristics and biases on team performance across various settings.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] By simulating interactions between agents—each representing individual team members with distinct traits and biases—this modeling approach enables researchers to explore how these factors collectively influence the dynamics and outcomes of team performance.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Consequently, agent-based modeling provides a nuanced understanding of team science, facilitating a deeper exploration of the subtleties and variabilities inherent in team-based collaborations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Prior to, and during the 2008 financial crisis, interest has grown in ABMs as possible tools for economic analysis.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs do not assume the economy can achieve equilibrium and "representative agents" are replaced by agents with diverse, dynamic, and interdependent behavior including herding.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs take a "bottom-up" approach and can generate extremely complex and volatile simulated economies.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs can represent unstable systems with crashes and booms that develop out of non-linear (disproportionate) responses to proportionally small changes.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A July 2010 article in *The Economist* looked at ABMs as alternatives to DSGE models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The journal *Nature* also encouraged agent-based modeling with an editorial that suggested ABMs can do a better job of representing financial markets and other economic complexities than standard models along with an essay by J.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Doyne Farmer and Duncan Foley that argued ABMs could fulfill both the desires of Keynes to represent a complex economy and of Robert Lucas to construct models based on microfoundations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Farmer and Foley pointed to progress that has been made using ABMs to model parts of an economy, but argued for the creation of a very large model that incorporates low level models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] By modeling a complex system of analysts based on three distinct behavioral profiles – imitating, anti-imitating, and indifferent – financial markets were simulated to high accuracy.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Results showed a correlation between network morphology and the stock market index.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] However, the ABM approach has been criticized for its lack of robustness between models, where similar models can yield very different results.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have been deployed in architecture and urban planning to evaluate design and to simulate pedestrian flow in the urban environment and the examination of public policy applications to land-use.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] There is also a growing field of socio-economic analysis of infrastructure investment impact using ABM's ability to discern systemic impacts upon a socio-economic network.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Heterogeneity and dynamics can be easily built in ABM models to address wealth inequality and social mobility.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been proposed as applied educational tools for diplomats in the field of international relations and for domestic and international policymakers to enhance their evaluation of public policy.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been applied in water resources planning and management, particularly for exploring, simulating, and predicting the performance of infrastructure design and policy decisions, and in assessing the value of cooperation and information exchange in large water resources systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agents for Systems are divided in two subcategories.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-supported systems deal with the use of agents as a support facility to enable computer assistance in problem solving or enhancing cognitive capabilities.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based systems focus on the use of agents for the generation of model behavior in a system evaluation (system studies and analyses).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Hallerbach et al. discussed the application of agent-based approaches for the development and validation of automated driving systems via a digital twin of the vehicle-under-test and microscopic traffic simulation based on independent agents.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Waymo has created a multi-agent simulation environment Carcraft to test algorithms for self-driving cars.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] It simulates traffic interactions between human drivers, pedestrians and automated vehicles.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] People's behavior is imitated by artificial agents based on data of real human behavior.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The basic idea of using agent-based modeling to understand self-driving cars was discussed as early as 2003.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Many ABM frameworks are designed for serial von-Neumann computer architectures, limiting the speed and scalability of implemented models.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since emergent behavior in large-scale ABMs is dependent of population size, scalability restrictions may hinder model validation.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Such limitations have mainly been addressed using distributed computing, with frameworks such as Repast HPC specifically dedicated to these types of implementations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] While such approaches map well to cluster and supercomputer architectures, issues related to communication and synchronization, as well as deployment complexity, remain potential obstacles for their widespread adoption.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A recent development is the use of data-parallel algorithms on Graphics Processing Units GPUs for ABM simulation.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] The extreme memory bandwidth combined with the sheer number crunching power of multi-processor GPUs has enabled simulation of millions of agents at tens of frames per second.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since Agent-Based Modeling is more of a modeling framework than a particular piece of software or platform, it has often been used in conjunction with other modeling forms.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] For instance, agent-based models have also been combined with Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This provides a useful combination where the ABM serves as a process model and the GIS system can provide a model of pattern.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Similarly, Social Network Analysis (SNA) tools and agent-based models are sometimes integrated, where the ABM is used to simulate the dynamics on the network while the SNA tool models and analyzes the network of interactions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Tools like GAMA provide a natural way to integrate system dynamics and GIS with ABM.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Verification and validation (V&V) of simulation models is extremely important.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Verification involves making sure the implemented model matches the conceptual model, whereas validation ensures that the implemented model has some relationship to the real-world.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Face validation, sensitivity analysis, calibration, and statistical validation are different aspects of validation.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A discrete-event simulation framework approach for the validation of agent-based systems has been proposed.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] A comprehensive resource on empirical validation of agent-based models can be found here.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] As an example of V&V technique, consider VOMAS (virtual overlay multi-agent system), a software engineering based approach, where a virtual overlay multi-agent system is developed alongside the agent-based model.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Muazi et al. also provide an example of using VOMAS for verification and validation of a forest fire simulation model.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Another software engineering method, i.e.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] Test-Driven Development has been adapted to for agent-based model validation.
[src:urban-metabolism/agent-based-model] This approach has another advantage that allows an automatic validation using unit test tools.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is broadly defined as an integrative approach that examines the ecological, social and economic relationship within agricultural systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. refer to agroecology as the study of the interactions between plants, animals, humans and the environment within agricultural systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Francis *et al*. also use the definition in the same way, but thought it should be restricted to growing food.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is a holistic approach that seeks to reconcile agriculture and local communities with natural processes for the common benefit of nature and livelihoods.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is inherently multidisciplinary, including sciences such as agronomy, ecology, environmental science, sociology, economics, history and others.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The system properties of agroecosystems studied may include: productivity, stability, sustainability and equitability.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is not limited to any one scale; it can range from an individual gene to an entire population, or from a single field in a given farm to global systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Wojtkowski discusses the application of agroecology in agriculture, forestry and agroforestry in his 2002 book.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology can be described in many different approaches.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] One perspective emphasizes ecosystem agroecology, which draws from system ecology and focuses on understanding farms as integrated ecological systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] This approach analyzes energy flows, nutrient cycles, and the ecological interactions among biotic and abiotic components of an agroecosystem.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Other scholars identify distinct historical traditions within agroecology.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] (2003) characterize agroecology as an integrative discipline combining agronomy, ecology, sociology, and economics.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Within this view, what is often termed early integrative agroecology focuses on understanding interactions among plants, animals, humans, and their environment within agricultural landscapes.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Over time, diverse methodological approaches have emerged depending on the values and goals prioritized.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Some perspectives emphasize more quantitative, technology-driven, and ecological-analytical methods often described as “hard agroecology”.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] This multi-layered use of the term encompassing science, practice, and movement has enabled agroecology to expand from the field or farm scale to the broader food-system scale, integrating ecological, social, economic, and cultural dimensions.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] There are three varieties of agroecology that are both well defined and have a certification regime.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] These are firstly biodynamic farming, secondly organic agriculture, and thirdly Green Food (managed by China Green Food).
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] For producers, certification enables certainty and oversight and the opportunity for achieving a premium price.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] For consumers, certification provides confidence that the stated good intentions have translated into actual production practices.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Biodynamics is the oldest of the certified agroecologies, Organics is the most widely practised certified agroecology (in 188 countries), and Green Food is the newest certified agroecology and was developed in China.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The history of agroecology depends on whether it is considered a body of thought or a method of practice.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Many indigenous cultures around the world have historically applied, and still apply, practices that today would be recognized as agroecological knowledge.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Examples include Maori, Nahuatl, and many other indigenous peoples.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The Mexica people that inhabited Tenochtitlan pre-colonization of the Americas used a process called chinampas that in many ways mirrors the use of composting in sustainable agriculture today.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The use of agroecological practices such as nutrient cycling and intercropping occurs across hundreds of years and many different cultures.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Indigenous peoples also currently make up a large proportion of people using agroecological practices, and those involved in the movement to move more farming into an agroecological paradigm.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] According to Gliessman and Francis *et al*., agronomy and ecology were first linked with the study of crop ecology by Klages in 1928.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] This work is a study of where crops can best be grown.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Wezel *et al*. say the first mention of the term agroecology was in 1928, with the publication of the term by Basil Bensin.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. claim the German zoologist Friederichs was the first to use the name in 1930 in his book on the zoology of agriculture and forestry, followed by American crop physiologist Hansen in 1939, both using the word for the application of ecology within agriculture.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Tischler's 1965 book *Agrarökologie* may be the first to be titled 'agroecology'.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] He analyzed the different components (plants, animals, soils and climate) and their interactions within an agroecosystem as well as the impact of human agricultural management on these components.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] More books and articles using the concept of agroecosystems and the word agroecology started to appear in 1970s.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] According to Dalgaard *et al*., it probably was the concept of "process ecology" such as studied by Arthur Tansley in the 1930s which inspired Harper's 1974 concept of agroecosystems, which they consider the foundation of modern agroecology.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. claim Frederic Clements's investigations on ecology using social sciences, community ecology and a "landscape perspective" is agroecology, as well as Henry Gleason's investigations of the population ecology of plants using different scientific disciplines.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Ethnobotanist Efraim Hernandez X.'s work on traditional knowledge in Mexico in the 1970s led to new education programs in agroecology.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Works such as *Silent Spring* and *The Limits to Growth* caused the public to be aware of the environmental costs of agricultural production, which caused more research in sustainability starting in the 1980s.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The view that the socio-economic context are fundamental was used in the 1982 article *Agroecologia del Tropico Americano* by Montaldo, who argues that this context cannot be separated from agriculture when designing agricultural practices.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In 1985 Miguel Altieri studied how the consolidation of the farms and cropping systems impact pest populations, and Gliessman how socio-economic, technological, and ecological components gave rise to producer choices of food production systems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In 1995, Edens *et al*. in *Sustainable Agriculture and Integrated Farming Systems* considered the economics of systems, ecological impacts, and ethics and values in agriculture.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Several social movements have adopted agroecology as part of their larger organizing strategy.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Groups like La Via Campesina have used agroecology as a method for achieving food sovereignty.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology has also been utilized by farmers to resist global agricultural development patterns associated with the green revolution.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is an applied science that involves the adaptation of ecological concepts to the structure, performance, and management of sustainable agroecosystems.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In Latin America, agroecological practices have a long history and vary between regions but share three main approaches or levels: plot scale, farm scale, and food system scale.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology in Latin American countries can be used as a tool for providing both ecological, economic, and social benefits to the communities that practice it, as well as maintaining high biodiversity and providing refuges for flora and fauna in these countries.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Garí wrote two papers for the FAO in the early 2000s about using an agroecological approach which he called "agrobiodiversity" to empower farmers to cope with the impacts of the AIDS on rural areas in Africa.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In 2011, the first encounter of agroecology trainers took place in Zimbabwe and issued the Shashe Declaration.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In Ethiopia, the Private Sector Incentives and Investments (PSii) project, following in the footprints of the Alliance of Bioversity International and CIAT (International Center for Tropical Agriculture), exemplifies the practical application of agroecology in developing nations.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In October 2024, a PSii project in the Doyogena region of Ethiopia was awarded praise from local and agricultural officials.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The project stressed the importance of practices such as rotation of faba beans and wheat to help enhance soil health, reduce chemical reliance, and increase productivity.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] These initiatives were put in place to promote climate resilient methods of agriculture and to diversify the many clusters of wheat farms in the area.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The project has shown signs of immense success in both improvements in soil quality and crop yields, which has sparked conversations about possibilities of wider adoption in similar regions throughout the local area and throughout Africa.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] The European Commission supports the use of sustainable practices such as agroecology through the Green Deal and the Farm to Fork Strategy.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Academic research areas that focus on topics related to agriculture or ecology, such as agronomy, veterinary science, environmental science, and others, are heatedly debating which model of agriculture or agroecology should be supported through policy.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] Agricultural departments of different countries support agroecology to varying degrees, with the UN perhaps its most prominent proponent**.** Debates around agroecology often reflect broader tensions in land and resource management, and Puerto Rico offers several examples of these dynamics.
[src:urban-metabolism/agroecology] In recent years, conflicts have emerged over the conversion of agricultural land for large-scale solar energy projects, raising concerns among local farmers and environmental groups about food security, land sovereignty, and long-term projects of fertile soil.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He was a key figure in the early history of the Russian Social Democratic Labor Party, originally established 1898, and of its Bolshevik faction.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1904–1906, he published three volumes of the philosophic treatise *Empiriomonizm* (*Empiriomonism*), in which he tried to merge Marxism with the philosophy of Ernst Mach, Wilhelm Ostwald, and Richard Avenarius.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] His work later affected a number of Russian Marxist theoreticians, including Nikolai Bukharin and Dov Ber Borochov.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov co-founded the Bolsheviks in 1903, when they split with the Menshevik faction.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He was a rival within the Bolsheviks to Vladimir Lenin (1870–1924), Lenin concentrated on undermining Bogdanov's reputation as a philosopher.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1909 he published a scathing book of criticism entitled *Materialism and Empiriocriticism*, assaulting Bogdanov's position and accusing him of philosophical idealism.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In June 1909, Bogdanov was defeated by Lenin at a Bolshevik mini-conference in Paris organized by the editorial board of the Bolshevik magazine *Proletary* and was expelled from the Bolsheviks.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He subsequently established his own faction Vpered.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Following the Russian Revolutions of 1917, when the Bolsheviks came to power in the collapsing Russian Republic, he was an influential critic of the Bolshevik government and Lenin from a Marxist leftist perspective during the first decade of the subsequent Soviet Union in the 1920s.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov received training in medicine and psychiatry.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] His wide scientific and medical interests ranged from the universal systems theory to the possibility of human rejuvenation through blood transfusion.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He invented an original philosophy called "tectology", now regarded as a forerunner of systems theory.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He was also an economist, culture theorist, science fiction writer, and political activist.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Lenin depicted him as one of the "Russian Machists".
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] A Russian born in Belarus, Alexander Malinovsky was born in Sokółka, Russian Empire (now Poland), into a rural teacher's family, the second of six children.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He attended the Gymnasium at Tula, which he compared to a barracks or prison.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He was awarded a gold medal when he graduated.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Upon completion of the gymnasium, Bogdanov was admitted to the Natural Science Department of Imperial Moscow University.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In his autobiography, Bogdanov reported that, while studying at Moscow University, he joined the Union Council of Regional Societies and was arrested and exiled to Tula because of it.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] The head of the Moscow Okhrana had used an informant to acquire the names of members of the Union Council of Regional Societies, which included Bogdanov's name.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] On October 30, 1894, students rowdily demonstrated against a lecture by the history Professor Vasily Klyuchevsky who, despite being a well-known liberal, had written a favourable eulogy for the recently deceased Tsar Alexander III of Russia.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Punishment of a few of the students was seen as so arbitrary and unfair that the Union Council requested a fair reexamination of the issue.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] That very night, the Okhrana arrested all the students on the list mentioned above – including Bogdanov – all of whom were expelled from the university and banished to their hometowns.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Expelled from Moscow State University, he enrolled as an external student at the University of Kharkov, from which he graduated as a physician in 1899.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov remained in Tula from 1894 to 1899, where – since his own family was living in Sokółka – he lodged with Alexander Rudnev, the father of Vladimir Bazarov, who became a close friend and collaborator in future years.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Here he met and married Natalya Bogdanovna Korsak, who, as a woman, had been refused entrance to the university.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] She was eight years older than he was and worked as a nurse for Rudnev.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Malinovsky adopted the pen name that he used when he wrote his major theoretical works and his novels from her patronym.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Alongside Bazarov and Ivan Skvortsov-Stepanov he became a tutor in a workers' study circle.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] This was organised in the Tula Armament Factory by Ivan Saveliev, whom Bogdanov credited with founding Social Democracy in Tula.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] During this period, he wrote his *Brief course of economic science*, which was published – "subject to many modifications made for the benefit of the censor" – only in 1897.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He later said that this experience of student-led education gave him his first lesson in proletarian culture.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In autumn 1895, he resumed his medical studies at the university of Kharkiv (Ukraine) but still spent much time in Tula.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He came across the works of Lenin in 1896, particularly the latter's critique of Peter Berngardovich Struve.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1899, he graduated as a medical doctor and published his next work, "Basic elements of the historical perspective on nature".
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, because of his political views, he was also arrested by the Tsar's police, spent six months in prison, and was exiled to Vologda.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov dated his support for Bolshevism from autumn of 1903.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Early in 1904, the Bolsheviks in Geneva sent Martyn Liadov to seek out supporters in Russia.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He found a sympathetic group of revolutionaries, including Bogdanov, in Tver.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov was then sent by the Tver Committee to Geneva, where he was greatly impressed by Lenin's *One Step Forward, Two Steps Back* (published in May 1904).
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Back in Russia at the time of the 1905 Revolution, Bogdanov was arrested on 3 December 1905 and held in prison until 27 May 1906.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Upon release, he was exiled for three years to Bezhetsk in the Tver Governorate.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, he obtained permission to spend his exile abroad, and joined Lenin in Kokkola, Finland.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] For the next six years, Bogdanov was a major figure among the early Bolsheviks, second only to Lenin in influence.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] His work later affected a number of Russian Marxist theoreticians, including Nikolai Bukharin.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1907, he helped organize the 1907 Tiflis bank robbery with both Lenin and Leonid Krasin.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1908 he joined Bazarov, Lunacharsky, Berman, Helfond, Yushkevich and Suvorov in a symposium *Studies in the Philosophy of Marxism* which espoused the views of the Russian Marxists.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] By mid-1908, the factionalism within the Bolsheviks had become irreconcilable.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] A majority of Bolshevik leaders either supported Bogdanov or were undecided between him and Lenin.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Lenin concentrated on undermining Bogdanov's reputation as a philosopher.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He joined his brother-in-law Anatoly Lunacharsky, Maxim Gorky, and other Vperedists on the island of Capri, where they started the Capri Party School for Russian factory-workers.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1910, Bogdanov, Lunacharsky, Mikhail Pokrovsky, and their supporters moved the school to Bologna, where they continued teaching classes until 1911, while Lenin and his allies soon started the Longjumeau Party School just outside of Paris.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov broke with the *Vpered* in 1912 and abandoned revolutionary activities.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] After six years of his political exile in Europe, Bogdanov returned to Russia in 1914, following the political amnesty declared by Tsar Nicholas II as part of the festivities connected with the tercentenary of the Romanov Dynasty.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov was drafted soon after the outbreak of World War I and was assigned as a junior regimental doctor with the 221st Smolensk infantry division in the Second Army commanded by General Alexander Samsonov.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In the Battle of Tannenberg, August 26–30, the Second Army was surrounded and almost completely destroyed, but Bogdanov survived because he had been sent to accompany a seriously wounded officer to Moscow.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However following the Second Battle of the Masurian Lakes, he succumbed to a nervous disorder and subsequently became junior house surgeon at an evacuation hospital.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1916 he wrote four articles for *Vpered* which provided an analysis of the World War I and the dynamics of war economies.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He attributed a central role to the armed forces in the economic restructuring of the belligerent powers.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He saw the army as creating a "consumers' communism" with the state taking over ever-increasing parts of the economy.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] At the same time military authoritarianism had also spread to civil society.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] This created the conditions for two consequences: consumption-led war communism and the destruction of the means of production.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He thus predicted that even after the war, the new system of state capitalism would replace that of finance capitalism even though the destruction of the forces of production would cease.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov had no party-political involvement in the Russian Revolution of 1917, although he did publish a number of articles and books about the events that unfurled around him.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He supported the Zimmerwaldist programme of "peace without annexations or indemnities".
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He deplored the Provisional Government's continued prosecution of the war.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] After the July Days, he advocated "revolutionary democracy" as he now considered the socialists capable of forming a government.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, he viewed this as a broad-based socialist provisional government that would convene a Constituent Assembly.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In May 1917, he published *Chto my svergli* in *Novaya Zhizn*.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Here he argued that between 1904 and 1907, the Bolsheviks had been "decidedly democratic" and that there was no pronounced cult of leadership.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, following the decision of Lenin and the émigré group around him to break with *Vpered* in order to unify with the Mensheviks, the principle of leadership became more pronounced.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] After 1912, when Lenin insisted on splitting the Duma group of the RSDLP, the leadership principle became entrenched.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, he saw this problem as not being confined to the Bolsheviks, noting that similar authoritarian ways of thinking were shown in the Menshevik attitude to Plekhanov, or the cult of heroic individuals and leaders amongst the Narodniks.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] At the beginning of February 1918, Bogdanov denied that the Bolsheviks' October seizure to power had constituted a conspiracy.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Rather, he explained that an explosive situation had arisen through the prolongation of the war.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He pointed to a lack of cultural development in that all strata of society, whether the bourgeoisie, the intelligentsia, or the workers, had shown a failure to resolve conflicts through negotiation.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He described the revolution as being a combination of a peasant revolution in the countryside and a soldier-worker revolution in the cities.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He regarded it as paradoxical that the peasantry expressed itself through the Bolshevik party rather than through the Socialist Revolutionaries.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He analysed the effect of the First World War as creating 'War Communism', which he defined as a form of 'consumer communism', which created the circumstances for the development of state capitalism.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He saw military state capitalism as a temporary phenomenon in the West, lasting only as long as the war.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, thanks to the predominance of the soldiers in the Bolshevik Party, he regarded it as inevitable that their backwardness should predominate in the re-organisation of society.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Instead of proceeding in a methodical fashion, the pre-existing state was simply uprooted.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He refused multiple offers to rejoin the party and denounced the new regime as similar to Aleksey Arakcheyev's arbitrary and despotic rule in the early 1820s.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1918, Bogdanov became a professor of economics at the University of Moscow and director of the newly established Socialist Academy of Social Sciences.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Between 1918 and 1920, Bogdanov co-founded the proletarian art movement Proletkult and was its leading theoretician.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In his lectures and articles, he called for the total destruction of the "old bourgeois culture" in favour of a "pure proletarian culture" of the future.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] It was also through Proletkult that Bogdanov's educational theories were given form with the establishment of the Moscow Proletarian University.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Later in that month, the president of Proletkult was removed, and Bogdanov lost his seat on its Central Committee.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He withdrew from the organization completely in 1921–1922.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov gave a lecture to a club at Moscow University, which, according to Yakov Yakovlev, included an account of the formation of Vpered and reiterated some of the criticisms Bogdanov had made at the time of the individualism of certain leaders.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Yakovlev further claimed that Bogdanov discussed the development of the concept of proletarian culture up to the present day and discussed to what extent the Communist Party saw Proletkult as a rival.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov hinted at the prospect of a new International that might emerge if there were a revival of the socialist movement in the West.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He said he envisaged such an International as merging political, trade union, and cultural activities into a single organisation.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Yakovlev characterised these ideas as Menshevik, pointing to the refusal of *Vpered* to acknowledge the authority of the 1912 Prague Conference.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Meanwhile, *Workers' Truth* had received publicity in the Berlin-based Menshevik journal *Sotsialisticheskii Vestnik*, and they also distributed a manifesto at the 12th Bolshevik Congress and were active in the industrial unrest which swept Moscow and Petrograd in July and August 1923.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] On 8 September 1923, Bogdanov was among a number of people arrested by the GPU (the Soviet secret police) on suspicion of being involved in them.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He demanded to be interviewed by Felix Dzerzhinsky, to whom he explained that while he shared a range of views with *Workers' Truth*, he had no formal association with them.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He was released after five weeks on 13 October; however, his file was not closed until a decree passed by the Supreme Soviet of the USSR on 16 January 1989.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] He wrote about his experiences under arrest in *Five weeks with the GPU*.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1922 whilst visiting London to negotiate the Anglo-Soviet Trade Agreement, Bogdanov acquired a copy of the British surgeon Geoffrey Keynes's book *Blood Transfusion*.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Returning to Moscow, he founded the Institute for Haematology and Blood Transfusions in 1924-25 and started blood transfusion experiments, apparently hoping to achieve eternal youth or at least partial rejuvenation.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Lenin's sister Maria Ulyanova was among many who volunteered to take part in Bogdanov's experiments.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] After undergoing 11 blood transfusions, he remarked with satisfaction the improvement of his eyesight, suspension of balding, and other positive symptoms.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] His fellow revolutionary Leonid Krasin wrote to his wife that "Bogdanov seems to have become 7, no, 10 years younger after the operation".
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] In 1925–1926, Bogdanov founded the Institute for Haematology and Blood Transfusions, which was later named after him.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] A later transfusion in 1928 cost him his life, when he took the blood of a student suffering from malaria and tuberculosis.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] The student injected with his blood made a complete recovery.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Loren Graham) have speculated that his death may have been a suicide, because Bogdanov wrote a highly nervous political letter shortly beforehand.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, his death could be attributed to the adverse effects of blood transfusion, which were poorly understood at the time.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Both Bogdanov's fiction and his political writings imply that he expected the coming revolution against capitalism to lead to a technocratic society.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] This was because the workers lacked the knowledge and initiative to seize control of social affairs for themselves as a result of the hierarchical and authoritarian nature of the capitalist production process.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] However, Bogdanov also considered that the hierarchical and authoritarian mode of organization of the Bolshevik party was also partly to blame, although Bogdanov considered at least some such organization necessary and inevitable.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov served as an inspiration for the character Arkady Bogdanov in Kim Stanley Robinson's science-fiction novels the Mars Trilogy.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] It is revealed in 'Blue Mars' that Arkady is a descendant of Alexander Bogdanov.
[src:urban-metabolism/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov is also the protagonist of the novel *Proletkult* (2018) by Italian collective Wu Ming.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] Classic liberal arts curriculum from the St.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] John's College in Annapolis, Maryland, a M.A. in Higher Education Administration from the George Washington University in Washington, D.C., and a Ph.D. from the University of Maryland, College Park, in administration with a concentration in cybernetics.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] Leonard is a consultant under the auspices of The Complementary Set, especially applications of the Viable System Model, a part-time University Teacher, Licensee T.S.I. and a representative of the Cwarel Isaf Institute.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] Currently she is the Director of Team Syntegrity Inc. in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] She was president of the American Society for Cybernetics from 2002 to 2004, and was elected president for 2009–2010 of the International Society for the Systems Sciences.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] Allenna Leonard was Stafford Beer’s partner in life and at work from 1981 until his death in 2002.
[src:urban-metabolism/allenna-leonard] She states on her web page that she is committed to continuing to use and publicize his work, and that her special interest is using Syntegration as a forum for democratic dialogue, especially on issues of public importance.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport was born in Lozova, Kharkov Governorate, Russia (in today's Kharkiv Oblast, Ukraine) into a secular Jewish family.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1922, he moved to the United States, and in 1928 became a naturalized citizen.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He started studying music in Chicago and continued with piano, conducting and composition at the Vienna Hochschule für Musik where he studied from 1929 to 1934.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] However, due to the rise of Nazism, he found it impossible to make a career as a pianist.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He shifted his career into mathematics, completing a Ph.D. in mathematics under Otto Schilling and Abraham Adrian Albert at the University of Chicago in 1941 on the thesis *Construction of Non-Abelian Fields with Prescribed Arithmetic*.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] According to *The Globe and Mail*, he was a member of the American Communist Party for three years, but quit before enlisting in the U.S.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Army Air Forces in 1941, serving in Alaska and India during World War II.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] After the war, he joined the Committee on Mathematical Biology at the University of Chicago (1947–54), publishing his first book, *Science and the Goals of Man*, co-authored with semanticist S.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He also received a one-year fellowship at the prestigious Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences at Stanford University.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] From 1955 to 1970, Rapoport was Professor of Mathematical Biology and Senior Research Mathematician at the University of Michigan, as well as founding member, in 1955, of the Mental Health Research Institute (MHRI) at the University of Michigan.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1970, during the Vietnam War, Rapoport moved to Toronto "to live in a country that was not committed to a messianic role—a small peaceful country with no aspiration to major power status".
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He was appointed professor of mathematics and psychology at the University of Toronto (1970–79).
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] The university appointed him professor emeritus in 1980.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He lived in bucolic Wychwood Park overlooking downtown Toronto, a neighbour of Marshall McLuhan.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] On his retirement from the University of Toronto, he became director of the Institute of Advanced Studies (Vienna) until 1983.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] University of Toronto appointed him professor of peace studies in 1984, a position he held until 1996, but continued to teach until 2000.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1984 he co-founded Science for Peace, was elected president and remained on its executive until 1998.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1954 Anatol Rapoport co-founded the Society for General Systems Research, along with the researchers Ludwig von Bertalanffy, Ralph Gerard, and Kenneth Boulding.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He became president of the Society for General Systems Research in 1965.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Anatol Rapoport died of pneumonia in Toronto.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He was survived by his wife Gwen, daughter Anya, and sons Alexander and Anthony.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport contributed to general systems theory, to mathematical biology, and to the mathematical modeling of social interaction and stochastic models of contagion.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He combined his mathematical expertise with psychological insights into the study of game theory, social networks, and semantics.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport extended these understandings into studies of psychological conflict, dealing with nuclear disarmament and international politics.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His autobiography, *Certainties and Doubts: A Philosophy of Life*, was published in 2001.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] An article celebrating his legacy and thinking includes a career overview alongside testimonials by scholars and family that provide a glimpse of Anatol Rapoport, the scientist and the person.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Philosopher and physicist Mario Bunge called Rapoport a polymath whose work Bunge found congenial because of its applicability to real-life problems, its use of mathematics, and its "avoidance of holistic blabber".
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport had a versatile mind, working in mathematics, psychology, biology, game theory, social network analysis, and peace and conflict studies.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] For example, he pioneered in the modeling of parasitism and symbiosis, researching cybernetic theory.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] This went on to give a conceptual basis for his lifelong work in conflict and cooperation.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Among many other well-known books on fights, games, violence, and peace, Rapoport was the author of over 300 articles and of "Two-Person Game Theory" (1966) and "N-Person Game Theory" (1970).
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He analyzed contests in which there are more than two sets of conflicting interests, such as war, diplomacy, poker, or bargaining.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His work led him to peace research, including books on *The Origins of Violence* (1989) and *Peace, An Idea Whose Time Has Come* (1993).
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In the 1980s, he won a computer tournament which was based on Robert Axelrod's *The Evolution of Cooperation* and was designed to further understanding of the ways in which cooperation could emerge through evolution.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] The contenders had to present programs that could play iterated games of the prisoner's dilemma and these were pitted against each other.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport's entry, Tit-for-Tat, has only four lines of code.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] The program opens by cooperating with its opponent.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] It then plays exactly as the other side played in the previous game.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] If the other side defected in the previous game, the program also defects; but only for one game.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] If the other side cooperates, the program continues to cooperate.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] According to *Peace Magazine* author/editor Metta Spencer, the program "punished the other player for selfish behaviour and rewarded her for cooperative behaviour—but the punishment lasted only as long as the selfish behaviour lasted.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] This proved to be an exceptionally effective sanction, quickly showing the other side the advantages of cooperating.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His children report that he was a strong chess player but a bad poker player because he non-verbally revealed the strength of his hands.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport was an early developer of social network analysis.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His original work showed that one can measure large networks by profiling traces of flows through them.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] This enables learning about the speed of the distribution of resources, including information, and what speeds or impedes these flows—such as race, gender, socioeconomic status, proximity, and kinship.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] This work linked social networks to the diffusion of innovation, and by extension, to epidemiology.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport's empirical work traced the spread of information within a school.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] It prefigured the study of degrees of separation by showing the rapid spread of information in a population to almost all—but not all—school members (see references below).
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His work on random nets predates the random graphs as defined by the Erdős–Rényi model and independently by Edgar Gilbert.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport is also the originator of the theory behind the interpretation of bias in social networks, which pertains to the extent to which a network deviates from a random base model.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He introduced what is now known as "preferential attachment mechanism" in biased networks.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] It is a stochastic process that involves connected nodes that snowball into more connections.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport also published an article that outlined a probabilistic approach to animal sociology, which is one of the earliest efforts at modeling simple social structures.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] According to Thomas Homer-Dixon in the *Toronto Globe and Mail*, Rapoport "became anti-militarist quite soon after World War II.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] The idea of military values became anathema".
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He was a leading organizer of the first teach-ins against the Vietnam War at the University of Michigan, a model that spread rapidly throughout North America.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He told at a teach-in: "By undertaking the war against Vietnam, the United States has undertaken a war against humanity…This war we shall not win".
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He said he was an abolitionist, rather than a total pacifist: "I'm for killing the institution of war".
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1968, he signed the "Writers and Editors War Tax Protest" pledge, vowing to refuse tax payments in protest against the Vietnam War.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] As a result of his opposition to the Vietnam War, J.Edgar Hoover considered Rapoport a Communist, and organized FBI agents to write letters to the president of the University of Michigan, the Governor of Michigan and others.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] This smear campaign drove him from Ann Arbor to the University of Toronto.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport returned to the University of Toronto to become the founding (and unpaid) Professor of Peace and Conflict Studies programme, working with George Ignatieff and Canada's Science for Peace organization.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] As its sole professor at the start, he used a rigorous, interdisciplinary approach to the study of peace, integrating mathematics, politics, psychology, philosophy, science, and sociology.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] His main concern was to legitimize peace studies as a worthy academic pursuit.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] The Trudeau Centre for Peace and Conflict Studies continued to flourish at the University of Toronto under the leadership of Thomas Homer-Dixon, and, from 2008, under Ron Levi.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] When Rapoport began, there was one (unpaid) professor and twelve students.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 2007, there were three paid professors and ninety students.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Rapoport's students report that he was an engaged and inspiring professor who captured their attention, imagination and interest with his wide-ranging knowledge, passion for the subject, good humor, kind and generous spirit, attentiveness to student concerns, and animated teaching style.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] In 1981 Rapoport co-founded the international non-governmental organization Science for Peace.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He was recognized in the 1980s for his contribution to world peace through nuclear conflict restraint via his game theoretic models of psychological conflict resolution.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] He won the Lentz International Peace Research Prize in 1976.
[src:urban-metabolism/anatol-rapoport] Professor Rapoport was also a member of the editorial board of the *Journal of Environmental Peace* published by the International Innovation Projects at the University of Toronto.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] Wilden is credited with one of the first significant introductions to the work of Jacques Lacan in the English-speaking world, particularly in his role as one of Lacan's early English translators.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] Today Wilden's work (and consequent reputation) is arguably more influential in the fields of communication theory, ecology and social interaction.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] These fields of study evolved out of a long scholarly tradition of "interactional semiotics" that originated with Plato's Cratylus.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] Along with such figures as Gregory Bateson (i.e., *Steps to an Ecology of Mind*), R.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] Laing (i.e., *Sanity, Madness and the Family*), and Walker Percy (i.e., *Lost in the Cosmos*), Wilden is considered one of this tradition's contemporary (modern and postmodern) pioneers.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] With the appearance of *System and Structure* (1972), Wilden sought "to establish the necessity of an ecosystemic or ecological approach to communication and exchange in open systems of all types", to use his own words.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] In hindsight it is recognized that *System and Structure* was an early contribution to a "theory of self-referential systems".
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] According to Niklas Luhmann, this "theory of self-referential systems" is the second paradigm change in a "General System Theory" (the first change being the "open-systems" or "systems/environment" shift, a step that initially separated "systems theory" from the traditional "whole-parts" paradigm).
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] Wilden was a professor in the Communications Department at Simon Fraser University from the 1970s to the mid-1990s.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] He attended the University of Victoria, Victoria, British Columbia, 1960–1961, 1963–1965; and Johns Hopkins University, earning an MA in 1967 and PhD in 1968.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] His doctoral thesis was entitled *Psychoanalysis and the Language of the Self*.
[src:urban-metabolism/anthony-wilden] He died at the age of 84 in Burnaby, British Columbia.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] With deep roots in sociology, Karl Marx and fellow researcher Friedrich Engels may have been the first to raise concerns around issues which we would now call urban metabolism.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] In short, Marx and Engels found that when humans exerted such physical labour they ultimately altered the biophysical processes as well.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] This acknowledgement of altering the biophysical landscape is the first stepping stone for the creation of urban metabolism within social geography.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] They also used metabolism to describe the material and energy exchange between nature and society in as a critique of industrialization (1883) which created an interdependent set of societal needs brought into play through the concrete organization of human labour.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Marx advocated that urban metabolism becomes a power in itself (like capitalism), and will control society unless society is able to control it.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Later, in reaction against industrialization and coal use, Sir Patrick Geddes, a Scottish biologist, undertook an ecological critique of urbanization in 1885, making him the first scientist to attempt an empirical description of societal metabolism on a macroeconomic scale.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Through his experimental study of urbanization he established a physical budget for urban energy and material throughput by way of an input output table.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] "Geddes' table consisted of the sources of energy and materials transformed into products in three stages: (1) extraction of fuels and raw materials; (2) the manufacture and transport; and (3) exchange.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] It wasn't until 1965 when Abel Wolman fully developed and used the term urban metabolism in his work, "The Metabolism of Cities" which he developed in response to deteriorating air and water qualities in American cities.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] In this study Wolman developed a model which allowed him to determine the inflow and outflow rates of a hypothetical American City with a population of 1 million people.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] The model allows the monitoring and documentation of natural resources used (mainly water) and the consequential creation and out-put of waste.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Wolman's study highlighted the fact that there are physical limitations to the natural resources we use on a day-to-day basis and with frequent use, the compilation of waste can and will create problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] It also helped focus researchers and professionals of their time to focus their attention on the system wide impacts of consumption of goods and sequential production of waste within the urban environment.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Working off of Wolman's pioneering work in the 60s, environmentalist Herbert Girardet (1996) began to see and document his findings in the connection between urban metabolism and sustainable cities.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] In a circular cycle, there is nearly no waste and almost everything is re-used.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Girardet characterizes this as a natural world process.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] On the other hand, a 'linear' metabolism which is characterized as an urban world process has a clear resource in-put and waste out-put.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Girardet emphasizes that the accelerated use of linear metabolisms in urban environments is creating an impending global crisis as cities grow.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] This research has stayed mainly at a descriptive level and did not reach into the political or social forces of urban form and stages of flow.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] From this research there has been a strong theme in present literature on urban sustainability is that of the need to view the urban system as a whole if we are to best understand and solve the complex problems.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Odum, a systems ecologist, wanted to emphasize the dependence on the source of almost all energy on the planet: the sun.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Odum believed that previous research and development on urban metabolism was missing and did not account for qualitative differences of mass or energy flows.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Odum's study took this into count and he coined the term "emergy" to track and account for the metabolic flows by measuring the solar energy used directly or indirectly to make a product or deliver a service.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] This method also emphasizes the use of a standard unit of measurement to calculate energy, nutrient and waste movement in the biophysical system; the unit chosen was "solar equivalent joules" (sej).
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] At first glance, the notion to use standard units seems like a beneficial idea for calculating and comparing figures; in reality the ability to convert all urban processes into solar energy joules has proven to be a difficult feat, and difficult to understand.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] The UM approach has been applied several times to assess and describe urban flows and impacts related to them, using different tools such as Material Flow Analysis (MFA).
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] The MFA technique has become the mainstream school of urban metabolism because it uses more practical units that the public, workers, government officials and researchers can understand.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] There are four main uses of urban metabolism that are used today by urban planners and designers: sustainability reporting, urban greenhouse gas accounting, mathematical modelling for policy analysis and urban design.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] With the issue of sustainability at the core of many environmental issues today, one of the main uses of Urban Metabolism in the modern era is to track and record levels of sustainability in cities and regions around the world.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Urban metabolism collects important and very useful information about energy efficiency, material cycling, waste management and infrastructure in urban environments.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] The urban metabolism model records and analyzes environmental conditions and trends which are easily understood for policy makers and consequently comparable over time making it easier to find unhealthy patterns and develop a plan of action to better the level of sustainability.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Staying in line with the notion of sustainability, urban metabolism is also a helpful tool for tracking greenhouse gas emissions on a city or regional level.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] As mentioned above, with the proliferation of linear metabolisms such as cars, the production of greenhouse gases has increased exponentially since the birth and mass production of the automobile causing a problem for our atmosphere.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Urban metabolism has been proven to be a necessary tool for measuring levels of greenhouse gas because it is an out-put or waste product that is produced through human consumption.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] The model provides quantifiable parameters which allow officials to mark unhealthy levels of GHG emissions and again, develop a plan of action to lower them.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Aside from accounting applications, scholars have begun to develop mathematical models to quantify and predict levels of particles and nutrients within the urban metabolism model.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Through utilization of the 3 applications above, scholars and professionals are able to use urban metabolism as a design tool to create greener and more sustainable infrastructure from the beginning.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] By tracing flows of energy, materials and waste through urban systems as a whole, changes and alterations can be made to close the loops to create circular metabolisms where resources are recycled and almost no waste is produced.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Such initiatives are being made around the world with technology and inventions which make building green that much easier and accessible.
[src:urban-metabolism/urban-metabolism] Uses of the model are however not restricted to strictly functional analysis, as the model has been adapted to examine the relational aspects of urban relationships between infrastructure and citizens.
